            <h2 id="tips">Tips for Better Merge Results</h2>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">1</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Match page sizes before merging</strong>
                    <p>If your PDFs have different page sizes (e.g., one is A4 and another is Letter), the merged document will have mixed page sizes which looks unprofessional. Use a PDF editor to standardize page sizes first, or crop pages to match.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">2</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Add page numbers after merging</strong>
                    <p>Individual PDFs often have their own page numbering. After merging, use PdfToolStack's <a href="/number-pages">Add Page Numbers</a> tool to apply consistent sequential numbering to the entire combined document.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">3</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Compress after merging</strong>
                    <p>Large merged documents benefit from a compression pass. After downloading your merged PDF, run it through the <a href="/compress-pdf">Compress PDF tool</a> to reduce the final file size without losing quality.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="article-tip">
                <div class="article-tip-num">4</div>
                <div>
                    <strong>Remove blank pages first</strong>
                    <p>PDFs often have blank pages at the end or between sections. Use the <a href="/split-pdf">Split PDF tool</a> to extract and remove blank pages from individual files before merging to keep the final document clean.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

