            <div class="article-faq">
                <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Is there a limit to how many PDFs I can merge?</summary>
                    <p>With PdfToolStack's free tier, you can merge as many PDFs as you like as long as each individual file is under 25MB. Pro users can upload files up to 500MB each. There's no hard limit on the number of files in a single merge operation.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Will merging PDFs reduce their quality?</summary>
                    <p>No. Merging PDFs is a lossless operation — it combines the documents without any compression or quality reduction. The merged output is identical in quality to the individual source files. If you want to reduce the file size afterward, that's a separate compression step.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Can I merge password-protected PDFs?</summary>
                    <p>Password-protected PDFs need to be unlocked before they can be merged. Use PdfToolStack's <a href="/unlock-pdf">Unlock PDF tool</a> to remove the password, then merge the unlocked files.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Can I merge PDFs on my phone?</summary>
                    <p>Yes. PdfToolStack is fully responsive and works in mobile browsers on iOS and Android. The interface adapts to smaller screens while maintaining full functionality.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>Does merging PDFs combine bookmarks and hyperlinks?</summary>
                    <p>Internal bookmarks and hyperlinks within each individual PDF are preserved in the merged document. Cross-document links (links from one PDF that point to another) will not function after merging since both documents are now part of the same file.</p>
                </details>

                <details class="article-faq-item">
                    <summary>How do I merge PDFs on a Mac without software?</summary>
                    <p>On Mac, you can use the built-in Preview app: open one PDF, drag the other PDF's thumbnail into the sidebar, then export as a new PDF. For more control over page order and multiple files, an online tool like PdfToolStack gives a better experience.</p>
                </details>
